  "riddle": "1. Seek the page that recounts a nation's aquatic feats in a 2017 competition. How many competitors represented this land in the water?\n\n2. Now, take the number you discovered and sum its digits. What single digit do you arrive at?\n\n3. A new chapter awaits, chronicle the aquatic quests of 2019. What city played host to the fierce competitors that year?\n\n4. Reflecting back to the 2015 contests, how many male swimmers proudly carried their nation's colors in the water?\n\n5. Progress to 2013, and find out how many brave souls represented this nation at the championships.\n\n6. Dive back into the 2011 events; how many competitors took part under this banner?\n\n7. Calculate the equivalent of four meters in yards. How many yards does this distance represent?\n\n8. As you drift over to the 2024 event page, tally the total number of Kenyan competitors that filled the aquatic roster.\n\n9. Turn to a significant document detailing this nation’s legal framework. How many languages are recognized at the top of that article?\n\n10. Investigate the location of this constitutional document; what is its elevation above sea level?\n\n11. Nearby where this sacred text resides, how many parks can you explore?\n\n12. Combine the elevation from clue 10 with the park count from clue 11. What value does this subtraction unveil?\n\n13. In another place of reflection, seek the elevation at a garden named for freedom. What is its height?\n\n14. Reflect on the height from clue 13. What is the next prime number after that value?\n\n15. In a temple's shadow, how many hotels can be found near a notable mountain? Count them.\n\n16. With a chill in the air, convert 4 degrees Celsius into a Fahrenheit-scale offset. What number does it yield?\n\n17. For the value in clue 16, what is its largest prime factor?\n\n18. Compute the digital root from the sums of the results from clues 4 and 8. What single digit do you reveal?",
